headline: This Big Short Investor Is Betting Against AI. Is He Making a Big Mistake?
summary: The quote, attributed to legendary economist John Maynard Keynes, isn’t likely to be put to the test by Michael Burry, the famed investor who correctly bet against the housing market in 2006, but it’s still worth exploring.  Burry’s wagers against two of the market’s iconic artificial intelligence stocks—  Nvidia  and  Palantir  —were unveiled in a Securities and Exchange Commission filing published late Monday.  “When I hear short sellers trying to call the AI revolution into question it’s super triggering,”  Palantir  CEO Alex Karp told CNBC on Tuesday as his stock slumped 7% on Tuesday despite a blowout set of third quarter earnings last night.

headline: Microsoft Neocloud Deals Cross $60 Billion in AI Spending Frenzy
summary: The largest chunk of that spending — about $23 billion — is going to British startup Nscale, according to people familiar with the situation, who requested anonymity to discuss the previously undisclosed sum.  The arrangement with Nscale will give Microsoft access to about 200,000 of Nvidia Corp.’s latest GB300 chips at sites in the UK, Norway, Portugal and Texas.  Like its peers, the world’s largest software company is struggling to get data centers online quickly enough to meet demand from customers and internal teams developing artificial intelligence tools.

headline: Analysis-Amazon's $38 billion OpenAI deal shows it is no longer an AI laggard
summary: (Reuters) -Amazon's $38 billion cloud deal with OpenAI marks a major endorsement for the e-commerce giant's cloud business after recent setbacks, including ceding market share to rivals and an outage that disrupted large parts of the internet.  After years of leading the cloud computing industry with its highly profitable Amazon Web Services business, Amazon has watched Microsoft and Alphabet's Google snatch big-ticket contracts with their AI-steeped clouds.  Amazon was considered a laggard in the AI race by many investors because it was late to launch a flagship large language model and for failing to offer a consumer-facing chatbot like OpenAI's ChatGPT.

content.title: Analysis-Amazon's $38 billion OpenAI deal shows it is no longer an AI laggard
content.summary: (Reuters) -Amazon's $38 billion cloud deal with OpenAI marks a major endorsement for the e-commerce giant's cloud business after recent setbacks, including ceding market share to rivals and an outage that disrupted large parts of the internet.  After years of leading the cloud computing industry with its highly profitable Amazon Web Services business, Amazon has watched Microsoft and Alphabet's Google snatch big-ticket contracts with their AI-steeped clouds.  Amazon was considered a laggard in the AI race by many investors because it was late to launch a flagship large language model and for failing to offer a consumer-facing chatbot like OpenAI's ChatGPT.
